<subSubSection id="C33AC3C3FF8CFF8CE6D7FECCEFCBFE5D" pageId="14" pageNumber="163" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B9F9048FF8CFF8CE6D7FECCEFCBFE5D" blockId="14.[140,1108,307,1355]" pageId="14" pageNumber="163">
<emphasis id="B9544C5AFF8CFF8CE6D7FECCEF63FE84" bold="true" box="[140,267,307,333]" pageId="14" pageNumber="163">
<emphasis id="B9544C5AFF8CFF8CE6D7FECCEF6EFE84" box="[140,262,307,333]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="163" reason="1">Diagnosis</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
The appearance of the epigyne is characteristic with a large rectangular notch on the posterior margin of the epigynal plate and the short converging ducts seen through the cuticle.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33AC3C3FF8CFF8CE6E2FE62EC5AFE34" pageId="14" pageNumber="163" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B9F9048FF8CFF8CE6E2FE62EC5AFE34" blockId="14.[140,1108,307,1355]" pageId="14" pageNumber="163">
<emphasis id="B9544C5AFF8CFF8CE6E2FE62EF28FE7E" bold="true" box="[185,320,413,439]" pageId="14" pageNumber="163">
<emphasis id="B9544C5AFF8CFF8CE6E2FE62EF53FE7E" box="[185,315,413,439]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="163" reason="1">Etymology</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
The specific name is a Latinised form of the Greek for “household” and “knowledge” and is used in its modern sense of “environmentally friendly”, referring to its occurrence in an intercrop.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
